Here is the test without manager change. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/531635/ Obviously, ldap's test failed."}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2018-01-09 20:45:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

Okay, I rabbitholed a little on this one but I'm convinced you're right, if ldap is the only identity backend then my suggestion doesn't work. However, I still think that special-casing each backend is problematic. First, it's a backwards compatibility issue for out-of-tree drivers since they need to suddenly include the new class parameter. Second, the problem exists for all identity backends, but this only fixes it for the sql and ldap backends, leaving out-of-tree backends still broken. So that makes me think that instead of removing the changes from the manager, ALL of the changes should be in the manager, plus the fixes in the shadow backend. Something like this works for me and passes tests, including the test you added: http://paste.openstack.org/show/641540/

There might still be bugs in that, but the logic is: if the filter has federated attributes, it's shadow-backend only ; else you must query both the identity backend and the federated backend unconditionally and merge the results. The tricky part is with the driver hints since that object gets changed behind the scenes by each backend call, so a copy must be used for the second query."}, {'account_id': 15054, 'date': '2018-01-10 06:43:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

> Okay, I rabbitholed a little on this one but I'm convinced you're
 > right, if ldap is the only identity backend then my suggestion
 > doesn't work. However, I still think that special-casing each
 > backend is problematic. First, it's a backwards compatibility issue
 > for out-of-tree drivers since they need to suddenly include the new
 > class parameter. Second, the problem exists for all identity
 > backends, but this only fixes it for the sql and ldap backends,
 > leaving out-of-tree backends still broken. So that makes me think
 > that instead of removing the changes from the manager, ALL of the
 > changes should be in the manager, plus the fixes in the shadow
 > backend. Something like this works for me and passes tests,
 > including the test you added: http://paste.openstack.org/show/641540/
 > 
 > There might still be bugs in that, but the logic is: if the filter
 > has federated attributes, it's shadow-backend only ; else you must
 > query both the identity backend and the federated backend
 > unconditionally and merge the results. The tricky part is with the
 > driver hints since that object gets changed behind the scenes by
 > each backend call, so a copy must be used for the second query.

Cool. It's better. I'll update it soon."}, {'account_id': 15054, 'date': '2018-01-10 07:08:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 15054, 'date': '2018-01-10 09:27:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

commit_message:
Fix list users by name

When attempting to filter users by name, it works
for local users, but doesn't work for federated users.

This patch fixed this error.

Change-Id: I1bee51c2be81dbddd9d849731ab53728c86b2765
Closes-bug: #1738895

The doc team helped me on this review like the following:

 [10:38] <oomichi> hi, can I get help related to openstackdocstheme?
 [10:38] <oomichi> on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/539851 we found inconsistent value on bug_tag, what is the best value for?
 [10:45] <dhellmann> oomichi : when you say you found inconsistent values, do you mean in other projects?
 [10:46] <oomichi> dhellmann: yeah, right. The value is different between projects. masayukig did put a good investigation result on the above review
 [10:47] <oomichi> he checked 284 repos
 [10:47] <oomichi> 220repos: doc/source/conf.py:bug_tag = ''"
 [10:48] <AJaeger> oomichi: each project can define it as they want.

 [10:48] <oomichi> ..
 [10:48] <AJaeger> oomichi: it's helps you - if you don#t need it, you don't need it ;)
 [10:48] <AJaeger> oomichi: if you set it, it tags the bug directly
 [10:48] <oomichi> AJaeger: thanks for your advice :)
 [10:49] <AJaeger> oomichi: we can update the documentation to recommend some values, e.g. to use doc instead of documentation.
 [10:49] * AJaeger would review such a change favorably
 [10:50] <oomichi> AJaeger: cool, that will be helpful for people like us :)

Add 'doc' tag for bug link on doc theme

This commit adds 'doc' tag for a bug link on the
openstackdocstheme config. This configuration is used for
documentation bug basically. So, this should be good in most cases.

commit_message:
keystone: enable fernet across all CI

The UUID tokens are deprecated as of the Pike release and they
will be removed in 2 releases.  The deployment choice should
be Fernet so we should test that extensively.

Change-Id: I7d9f8782afc2cb636e69e8dd1e16c68182c38959

commit_message:
config-download: remove HostnameMap management

tripleo-quickstart now provides a cool interface to configure the
HostnameMap per job architecture, depending on the number of nodes and
their roles.
Let's use it so we can enable config-download for all kind
of multinode jobs.

Change-Id: Ia13b3adf91324bb96cd13281c7469412734e151b

[{'created': '2018-01-31 11:26:31.000000000', 'message': 'Bind mount the database client settings in cinder_api_db_sync

cinder_api_db_sync does not use the database settings which are
generated by the puppet_config step. Consequently, it loses some
important client settings for accessing the DB, e.g. it breaks
when TLS everywhere is enabled.

Bind mount the tripleo.cnf file to expose the proper DB settings.

Change-Id: I17f3304d546eeb78803b4a3cc859255bfb3f71eb
Closes-Bug: #1746491
'}]
commit_message:
Bind mount the database client settings in cinder_api_db_sync

cinder_api_db_sync does not use the database settings which are
generated by the puppet_config step. Consequently, it loses some
important client settings for accessing the DB, e.g. it breaks
when TLS everywhere is enabled.

Bind mount the tripleo.cnf file to expose the proper DB settings.

Change-Id: I17f3304d546eeb78803b4a3cc859255bfb3f71eb
Closes-Bug: #1746491

commit_message:
ovs-lib: Pass string as udp port to ovsdb

ovsdb maps accept strings as values only. This patch converts integer to
be passed to ovsdb in case vxlan_udp_port config value is used.

Change-Id: Idba77939a80d80a4bc9625d10c8b37b23b91b9c5
Closes-bug: #1742931
(cherry picked from commit 622a137974dbe0ffec84149fc36d19e440bd18b2)

commit_message:
Remove step_tags_to_when from config download and fix sorting

We are now going to have 'when' in the upgrade_tasks directly
so no need to overwrite anymore (see depends-on).

This also changes the sorting of tasks and the order in which
they are written to the ansible playbook. We were previously
sorting on tags and this no longer works. Instead sort on the
step number given in the 'when:' value.

Closes-Bug: 1743758
Depends-On: I6adc5619a28099f4e241351b63377f1e96933810
Change-Id: I68c032c5f23393a77109f182541cc6bfcc019a41

- gate-instack-undercloud-puppet-syntax-4-centos-7 http://logs.openstack.org/44/437544/1/check/gate-instack-undercloud-puppet-syntax-4-centos-7/7ef6468/ : SUCCESS in 4m 49s'}, {'account_id': 12398, 'date': '2017-02-23 20:38:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Wow, that was quick, and it looks like a great start. I wonder if we should be calling these INSPECTION_ROUTED_SEGMENTS rather than INSPECTION_ROUTED_NETWORKS? It seems like that would fit better with the new Neutron routed networks schema when we finally integrate with that. The new schema is Network--[1..N]-->Segments--[1..N]-->Subnets, with Segments being equal to a physical network (which might have more than one subnet). On the other hand, many people will look at that and say "what's a segment?" since it's a new concept. I'm good either way, but wanted to bring it up for discussion.'}, {'account_id': 12398, 'date': '2017-02-23 20:39:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Alternatively, INSPECTION_ROUTED_SUBNETS would be another option.'}, {'account_id': 12398, 'date': '2017-02-23 20:51:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2017-02-23 20:57:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Regarding the naming, I don't have a strong opinion.
As a bit of an everything datacenter guy; mainly FC/iSCSI storage, networking; Network Segments to me simply sound like different L2 broadcast domains.

In your description, Segments, sound more like what I like what I would think about as leafs? Which essentially is also just different L2 broadcast domain, but the segments/leafs contain similar devices.

. . . I will change it to 'INSPECTION_ROUTED_SEGMENTS', it makes sense with `OS::Neutron::Segment` which I see in the bluprint."}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2017-02-23 21:17:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 12398, 'date': '2017-02-23 21:30:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

The schema of Network-->Segments-->Subnets is really a consequence of the original Neutron design which allowed multiple subnets on the same network, but in that case all subnets share one broadcast domain. I don't think many people have use cases for that model (maybe it's useful when migrating instances from one subnet to another without changing physical topology), but multiple subnets per physical segment was required in the routed networks model in order to ease migration from non-routed to routed networks. I don't think it's a problem if Ironic Inspector only supports one start/end address per declared network/segment for the time being. We can worry about support for multiple subnets when we work on Neutron/Ironic integration."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-02-23 22:34:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This looks really good, just one comment below.

I also had a question on upgrade. Currently we have network ctlplane and subnet ctlplane-subnet.  On upgrade, it looks like the network would be found and updated in _configure_neutron_network(). The subnet “ctlplane-subnet” would not be found and a new subnet, "subnet0" would be created in _ensure_neutron_subnet(), so we’d end up with 2 subnets in the ctlplane network, is that right?  I wonder if we should delete ctlplane-subnet if that is the case.'}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2017-04-12 17:38:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

> I also had a question on upgrade. Currently we have network
 > ctlplane and subnet ctlplane-subnet.  On upgrade, it looks like the
 > network would be found and updated in _configure_neutron_network().
 > The subnet “ctlplane-subnet” would not be found and a new subnet,
 > "subnet0" would be created in _ensure_neutron_subnet(), so we’d end
 > up with 2 subnets in the ctlplane network, is that right?  I wonder
 > if we should delete ctlplane-subnet if that is the case.

Thanks Bob, this is indeed a issue. 

I don't think we can delete the ctlplane-subnet. If there is an overcloud deployed we would have neutron ports associated to ctlplane-subnet for all overcloud nodes. So we need to transition the existing ctlplane-subnet.

if undercloud_operation == "upgrade":
    get_id_of_ctlplane_subnet
    update_ctlplane_subnet_name

could be sufficient?


If the user installs this version of instack-undercloud and does "openstack undercloud install" on an existing deployment it will also break.

Another issue is if a user change an existig subnet, e.g rename "subnetX" to "leafX"?


I need to set up a system locally and do some testing.


The missing check for NETWORK_GATWAY_DEFAULT and the typo are both unintentional. . . I will fix them, and commit the fix with the change to handle upgrade.'}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2017-04-13 14:06:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23: Code-Review-1

Fixing the masquerading, some pystache rendering issue due to quotes + iptables not supporting ! -d net1,net2,net3.

For each network step trough all routed network desitnations, and RETURN if match. 
If packet is not destined for any of the routed networks finally MASQUERADE.


In my test locally with two networks,  172.20.0.0/26 and 172.20.0.64/26 the following show POSTROUTING config:

[stack@ocataleafs ~]$ sudo iptables -t nat -L POSTROUTING -v 
Chain POSTROUTING (policy ACCEPT 3321 packets, 199K bytes)
 pkts bytes target     prot opt in     out     source               destination         
 3321  199K BOOTSTACK_MASQ  all  --  any    any     anywhere             anywhere            
 6708  403K nova-api-POSTROUTING  all  --  any    any     anywhere             anywhere            
 6708  403K nova-postrouting-bottom  all  --  any    any     anywhere             anywhere            
    0     0 MASQUERADE  all  --  any    !docker0  172.17.0.0/16        anywhere            
    0     0 MASQUERADE  all  --  any    eth0    172.20.0.0/26        anywhere            
    0     0 MASQUERADE  all  --  any    eth0    172.20.0.64/26       anywhere            

[stack@ocataleafs ~]$ sudo iptables -t nat -L BOOTSTACK_MASQ -v 
Chain BOOTSTACK_MASQ (1 references)
 pkts bytes target     prot opt in     out     source               destination         
    0     0 RETURN     all  --  any    any     172.20.0.0/26        192.168.122.1       
 3431  206K RETURN     all  --  any    any     172.20.0.0/26        172.20.0.0/26       
    0     0 RETURN     all  --  any    any     172.20.0.0/26        172.20.0.64/26      
    0     0 MASQUERADE  all  --  any    any     172.20.0.0/26        anywhere            
    0     0 RETURN     all  --  any    any     172.20.0.64/26       192.168.122.1       
    0     0 RETURN     all  --  any    any     172.20.0.64/26       172.20.0.0/26       
    0     0 RETURN     all  --  any    any     172.20.0.64/26       172.20.0.64/26      
    0     0 MASQUERADE  all  --  any    any     172.20.0.64/26       anywhere'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-05-14 16:03:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 37: Verified-1

(1 comment)

Would it make sense to remove the segment creation/update from undercloud.py?  We don't actually need segments for the undercloud and the ironic dhcp instance - we've verified that introspection works for Spine/Leaf on multiple subnets without segments.  We do need segments in a Spine/Leaf implementation for the Neutron dhcp for overcloud node provisioning, but we should be able to create the segment using Heat since Heat supports segments (we may need some changes to pass host_id etc).

In this way the default case (non-spine/leaf) does not have the added complexity of segments associated with the ctlplane subnet.  WDYT?"}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2017-05-25 13:42:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 40:

> (1 comment)
 > 
 > Would it make sense to remove the segment creation/update from
 > undercloud.py?  We don't actually need segments for the undercloud
 > and the ironic dhcp instance - we've verified that introspection
 > works for Spine/Leaf on multiple subnets without segments.  We do
 > need segments in a Spine/Leaf implementation for the Neutron dhcp
 > for overcloud node provisioning, but we should be able to create
 > the segment using Heat since Heat supports segments (we may need
 > some changes to pass host_id etc).
 > 
 > In this way the default case (non-spine/leaf) does not have the
 > added complexity of segments associated with the ctlplane subnet. 
 > WDYT?

I have been thinking about the same before. It does'nt make sense that we create Control Plane network via undercloud.py, and the other isolated networks via Heat THT as overcloud is deployed. Doing it all in THT would be better.

There might be one blocker, AFAIK we cannot make a Heat resource for something that already exist.
If we removed the ctlplane network/segment/subnet creation from undercloud.py how would we manage changes on update/upgrade of existing deployed undercloud? e.g changeing the allocation pool for the subnet, dns or gateway settings?

  We might not need to? It could be manual procedure?"}, {'account_id': 21909, 'date': '2017-05-25 15:21:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 40:

Harald - I was actually suggesting that we leave in the network/subnet creation as is currently done in the patch (I believe it needs to be done here so introspection can be done using this network) but just remove the segment creation.  The segment can be created by a THT if spine/leaf is implemented, as it does not already exist.'}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2017-05-26 13:19:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 40:

> Harald - I was actually suggesting that we leave in the
 > network/subnet creation as is currently done in the patch (I
 > believe it needs to be done here so introspection can be done using
 > this network) but just remove the segment creation.  The segment
 > can be created by a THT if spine/leaf is implemented, as it does
 > not already exist.

We cannot mix subnets associated with a segment and subnets not associated with a segment on the same neutron network. If we where to create "Network: ctlplane  + Subnet: ctlplane-subnet" only in undercloud.py we cannot add another subnet associated with a segment to the ctlplane network using THT later. If we had https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1692490 implemented to support migrationg subnets not associated with a segment to the segments model we could by default not use segments. However, I kind of like the "use segments always" approach. It will enforce every CI test to use them ensuring that we don't miss issues because CI does not use segments.

Introspection is not using Neutron networking, it is done using a separate dnsmasq process that bind to the br-ctlplane interface. I don't think any neutron network/subnet is needed for introspection to work. This is why I think the option to not create any neutron networks/segments/subnets in undercloud.py might be an option. However, I believe another reason to keep the neutron network/segment/subnet config in undercloud.py is that Ironic cleaning feature uses Neutron networking. I think it makes sense to enable the possibility to clean nodes before running THT?'}, {'account_id': 21909, 'date': '2017-05-26 14:09:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 40:

Thanks Harald.  I agree with leaving the segment implementation here, its a good point that it will be tested with CI. My main concern is affect on upgrades, but again this will now be tested if the segment is used here.

Note that I don't think we would be mixing segment and non-segment subnets if we associated ctlplane-subnet with a segment by THT in the overcloud, as there would only be this subnet, but lets stay with this implementation (once we can resolve the host_id binding issue)."}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2017-05-28 14:18:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 41.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2017-05-28 14:23:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 41:

 > > an overcloud we're not really proving much wrt the provisioning

 > >
 > > I think ideally we'd want to either delete the overcloud and
 > > redeploy after the undercloud upgrade, or do a scale out so we
 > have
 > > to provision another node.
 > 

I did the following test:

1. Install undercloud following Tripleo Docs.
2. Import nodes and introspect (2 nodes)
3. Deploy overcloud (1x Controller 1x Compute)
4. Import and introspect 1x additional node.
5. Install this patch using pip
6. Run openstack undercloud upgrade
7. Increated Compute count from 1 to 2
8. Re-run overcloud deploy to scale from 1 compute to 2 computes.

The screenlog, undercloud upgrade log and config file used is here: https://github.com/hjensas/437544-test"}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2018-02-06 02:44:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 93:

'}, {'created': '2017-03-09 18:22:59.000000000', 'message': "Tripleo routed networks ironic inspector, and Undercloud

Add a option 'routed_subnets', this is a list of named subnets.
For each routed_subnet a group in the configuration file is
expected. This group contain the options required to set up
dnsmasq for Ironic Inspector, as well as neutron ctlplane
subnets. (network_cidr, dhcp_start, dhcp_end, inspection_iprange
and network_gateway)

The configuration data is used to configure Inspector and
Neutron subnets on the ctlplane networks with the required tags
and per-subnet dhcp router options to enable inspection and
Ironic provisioning of nodes reaching the undercloud via DHCP-
relay on remote subnets.

NOTE! DHCP-relay on the Neutron subnets will need changes in
      the dhcp agent. It assumes Network == Broadcast domain.

'}, {'created': '2017-05-02 23:33:45.000000000', 'message': 'Tripleo routed networks ironic inspector, and Undercloud

Configure Inspector and Neutron subnets on the ctlplane networks
with the required tags and per-subnet dhcp router options to
enable inspection and Ironic provisioning of nodes reaching the
undercloud via DHCP-relay on remote networks.

Firewall rules, and static routes are created for the remote
networks.

The creation of Neutron networks and Subnets in the undercloud
is moved from ORC to undercloud.py

To allow DHCP via relay Neutron Segments are used. Support for
relay is WiP in the neutron dhcp code.

A number of options related to ctlplane network is deprecated.
More details in relesenotes.

Implements: blueprint tripleo-routed-networks-ironic-inspector

'}, {'created': '2017-05-16 09:47:11.000000000', 'message': 'Tripleo routed networks ironic inspector, and Undercloud

* Configure Inspector and Neutron subnets on the ctlplane networks
  with the required tags and per-subnet dhcp router options to
  enable inspection and Ironic provisioning of nodes reaching the
  undercloud via DHCP-relay on remote networks.
* Firewall rules, and static routes are created for the remote
  networks.
* Masquerading for external access for each routed network, if
  enabled.
* The creation of Neutron networks and Subnets in the undercloud
  is moved from ORC to undercloud.py
* To allow DHCP via relay Neutron Segments are used. Support for
  relay is WiP in the neutron dhcp code.

A number of options related to ctlplane network is deprecated.
More details in release notes.

Implements: blueprint tripleo-routed-networks-ironic-inspector
Implements: blueprint tripleo-routed-networks-deployment

Depends-On: I9cce7b8a19c1201435df0c6baac7be57c57847e6
Change-Id: I4b384bab2af9f6ba07a137a37f4098a00ce18bc0

commit_message:
Tripleo routed networks ironic inspector, and Undercloud

* Enable the neutron segments service_plugin for routed
  provider networks.
* Update controlplane network code to create segments
  for each subnet.

A number of options related to ctlplane network is deprecated.
More details in release notes.

Implements: blueprint tripleo-routed-networks-ironic-inspector
Implements: blueprint tripleo-routed-networks-deployment

Depends-On: I33804bfd105a13c25d6057e8414e09957939e8af
Change-Id: I4b384bab2af9f6ba07a137a37f4098a00ce18bc0

'}, {'created': '2017-06-19 12:39:38.000000000', 'message': 'Add subnet property to ctlplane network for server resources

The subnet property is added to puppet/role.role.j2.yaml as
`{{role}}CtlPlaneSubnet`. Roles with a different subnet specified
can be used to deploy a routed network architecture by using one
role per routed network.

This depends on a Heat change that improves network logic in server
resource to not replace the current port if new props match what is
on the current interface. Without this adding the subnet property on
update/upgrades would cause a port replacement, which in turn would
cause IPAM info in undercloud neutron to miss-match the deployed
overcloud nodes.

Depends-On: Iab75ec49b962617943017dcaf1b04b89f91a982e
Change-Id: I33804bfd105a13c25d6057e8414e09957939e8af
Implements: blueprint tripleo-routed-networks-deployment

'}, {'created': '2017-07-06 10:45:05.000000000', 'message': 'Add subnet property to ctlplane network for server resources

The subnet property is added to puppet/role.role.j2.yaml as
`{{role}}ControlPlaneSubnet`. Roles with a different subnet specified
can be used to deploy a routed network architecture by using one
role per routed network.

When enabling the neutron segments plug-in to support routed-networks
the neutron IPAM code will defer ipallocation unless the port create
request contain enough details. (Ref: LP Bug: #1695740) By adding the
subnet to port create request this change enables tripleo deployment
on an undercloud with Neutron segments plug-in and routed networks.

This depends on a Heat change that improves network logic in server
resource to not replace the current port if new props match what is
on the current interface. Without this adding the subnet property on
update/upgrades would cause a port replacement, which in turn would
cause IPAM info in undercloud neutron to miss-match the deployed
overcloud nodes.

Depends-On: Iab75ec49b962617943017dcaf1b04b89f91a982e
Change-Id: I33804bfd105a13c25d6057e8414e09957939e8af
Implements: blueprint tripleo-routed-networks-deployment
'}, {'created': '2017-07-07 12:49:48.000000000', 'message': 'Add subnet property to ctlplane network for server resources

The subnet property is added to puppet/role.role.j2.yaml as
`{{role}}ControlPlaneSubnet`. Roles with a different subnet specified
can be used to deploy a routed network architecture by using one
role per routed network.

When enabling the neutron segments plug-in to support routed-networks
the neutron IPAM code will defer ipallocation unless the port create
request contain enough details. (Ref: LP Bug: #1695740) By adding the
subnet to port create request this change enables tripleo deployment
on an undercloud with Neutron segments plug-in and routed networks.

This depends on a Heat change that improves network logic in server
resource to not replace the current port if new props match what is
on the current interface. Without this adding the subnet property on
update/upgrades would cause a port replacement, which in turn would
cause IPAM info in undercloud neutron to miss-match the deployed
overcloud nodes.

Depends-On: Iab75ec49b962617943017dcaf1b04b89f91a982e
Change-Id: I33804bfd105a13c25d6057e8414e09957939e8af
Implements: blueprint tripleo-routed-networks-deployment

commit_message:
Add subnet property to ctlplane network for server resources

The subnet property is added to puppet/role.role.j2.yaml as
`{{role}}ControlPlaneSubnet`. Roles with a different subnet specified
can be used to deploy a routed network architecture by using one
role per routed network.

When enabling the neutron segments plug-in to support routed-networks
the neutron IPAM code will defer ipallocation unless the port create
request contain enough details. (Ref: LP Bug: #1695740) By adding the
subnet to port create request this change enables tripleo deployment
on an undercloud with Neutron segments plug-in and routed networks.

This depends on a Heat change that improves network logic in server
resource to not replace the current port if new props match what is
on the current interface. Without this adding the subnet property on
update/upgrades would cause a port replacement, which in turn would
cause IPAM info in undercloud neutron to miss-match the deployed
overcloud nodes.

Depends-On: Iab75ec49b962617943017dcaf1b04b89f91a982e
Change-Id: I33804bfd105a13c25d6057e8414e09957939e8af

commit_message:
Add support for ceph-nfs manila backend

If ceph-nfs (ganesha) service is enabled, it's set up by ceph-ansible
and it can be used as a manila backend. Manila can be configured to use
ceph either directly (manila-cephfsnative-config-docker.yaml env file)
or through ganesha (environments/manila-cephfganesha-config-docker.yaml
env file).

Change-Id: Ib408c7827e5fba0c1b01388db26363806fc64370
Partially-Implements: blueprint nfs-ganesha

Updated doc regarding bundle usage

Allowing to get a shared ruby library directory will make things faster
for people running tests on multiple modules all the day.

commit_message:
Get message from websocket instead from zaqarclient directly

Use the websocket api to get and print the real time
ansible execution for minor update instead of using the
zaqarclient call directly.
This is safer and avoid brutal claim of the messages.

Change-Id: I7e324b9e037197082c23a19b4e4b8832daaf5aee

commit_message:
Skip stack in-progress check

Now that the undercloud uses convergence by default, restarting Heat
won't put the stack in FAILED state, which means you can't call deploy
again. Let's skip the check altogether, to let Heat handles it

Change-Id: I93f025995ee24ab62912e6a980e03c2d45acef25

commit_message:
Do not fail fencing configuration when instanceha is disabled

Right now we fail like this if fencing is enabled but instanceha is not:
"Error: Evaluation Error: Error while evaluating a Function Call, Could not find data item compute_instanceha_short_node_names in any Hiera
data file and no default supplied at /etc/puppet/modules/tripleo/manifests/fencing.pp:61:13 on node controller-0.localdomain"

Change-Id: I36691997bffc56cb4fe17b2f762e4d44d71dfe50
Closes-Bug: #1747643

commit_message:
keystone: support _member_ role management

Allow to let puppet-keystone managing _member_ role which is required
by Horizon. Can be enabled with keystone_enable_member parameter (disabled
by default.)

A patch in tripleo-heat-templates will activate this boolean to true so
Horizon deployments will trigger the role creation.

Change-Id: I5272f1fc199772043db48d29b0ea99a8bfff4ed5
Related-Bug: #1741066

commit_message:
Add default libvirt options to dev_privileged environment

This should enable deploying with this enabled via -E, previously
I'd only tested via -c which is inconsistent with the intended
use of the environments/* files I think.

Marking this as closing bug #1692976 as this provides a way to make
the VMs survive host reboots.

Change-Id: I1143f93d1d36654ae802f53781823364a761f588
Closes-Bug: #1692976

commit_message:
Revert "Set disable:true for oci-machine-register"

We don't need this code anymore, since it's now the default
in OCI, since:
https://github.com/projectatomic/oci-register-machine/commit/66691c3d0805c41e7336a364934e3e144e97a20f#diff-7a73afad76bf813b4d03daf6fbc18568

This reverts commit e9bce747833af94ce71fe76921bd53cb5df07964.

Closes-Bug: #1747473
Change-Id: Iddc8a35a20a745dba14456e4b57741ffec67cc80

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary lines from sample local.conf

Nova network service does not exist anymore, so no need to disable
it, as well as enable neutron as it is enabled by default. Heat is
not enabled by default, so there is no need to disable it.

Change-Id: I6dea2ec9bde717462b6974c001bc23b2ad8c6d94

commit_message:
Use registry service for load balancer actions

This uses the horizon angular registry service to register the
actions for load balancers. This makes the actions extensible and
allows plugins to easily modify existing actions and add new ones.

The other resources (listeners, pools, members, health monitors)
will be updated to use the registry service in follow on patches.

Partially-Implements: blueprint horizon-lbaas-v2-ui
Change-Id: I8f67758ed6c430cb32c13d69095018e300caa6e1

commit_message:
Add loading and error status to detail pages

This adds a loading indicator to detail pages and makes sure that the
page content is not displayed until fully loaded. This prevents the
pages from displaying with partial content and having the updated
values pop in. It also adds an error indicator with a message when
there is an error loading the page. The page content will not display
if there is an error. This prevents the user from seeing the page in
an error state with missing information and broken links.

Closes-Bug: #1561102
Change-Id: Idfa61b6d533ef15facbe4fdca698b14321d8a07b

commit_message:
Refactor row/batch actions

This change is just a refactor of some of the row and batch actions code.
No functionality changes should be present in this change.  Specifically,
this change moves all CRUD actions that still exist in the
'row-actions.service.js and 'batch-action.service.js' files and places
them in their own files.  Also included in this change are a few doc
cleanups/improvements as well as updating all action success messages,
not including load balancer actions, to be in the past tense, since these
actions are not asynchronous.

Closes-Bug: #1557718
Change-Id: Iffe55f8cc0527aa84afbac720a22b839e1d53dc5

commit_message:
DNS-Helper: Remove chart

The DNS-Helper chart was created to support early development of
openstack helm, it is no longer required, and causes more confusion
than help these days. This PS removes the chart.

(2 comments)

not sure, I understood completely on deadlock on read and will be applicable for our case. But if you feel strongly needed , then should be fine.

Apart from this some minor comments. Else, looks good.'}, {'account_id': 18591, 'date': '2018-02-07 19:45:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)

Hi Anusha!

Thanks for the comments. To summarize the deadlock situation, basically it's hard to be certain whether deadlock can or cannot happen in a particular read (it depends on specific backend and version, on indexing setup (indexes get locked too), on what other operations there are in congress). Given that it's very difficult to be sure, to me it makes sense to just uniformly apply the retry mechanism, which has negligible cost to performance or code complexity even if a deadlock never happens.

Given your review, I'll fix the import issues and merge. We can still make final changes on 2/8 just before we release RC1 if something important.

Thanks a lot!"}, {'account_id': 18591, 'date': '2018-02-07 19:46:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 18591, 'date': '2018-02-07 19:47:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2

Comments addressed. Merging now to be ready for RC1 release.'}]

commit_message:
DB operations retry on deadlock

Occassionally, the database backend may experience a deadlock error
in the normal course of operations.
It is standard practice to have the database client retry the
operation.

If retries continue to fail, eventually return to user with 500
error and description.

Closes-Bug: 1746139

Change-Id: Iffc9344d22d1b3c0408eca3cef11767bafd2c7c2

commit_message:
Replace virtualenv-tools by a script

virtualenv-tools has a bug which gets triggered in gates: it can't
change the shebang of a virtualenv python bin/ files if they
were generated with a virtualenv script whose shebang ends with
python2 instead of python.

Because we can't modify virtualenv-tools, we use shell scripts
instead.

Change-Id: I02b7f6ce8c550a7d64dee908876ccb9a146e959a
Partial-Bug: #1741634

commit_message:
Support accessing all clusters/templates across projects

As an admin user, I'd like to access all clusters or templates across
all projects for operation purpose. Similar function is supported by
most of the other services, like Nova, Neutron, Cinder, Heat, etc.

Related-Bug: #1740982

Change-Id: Icaba09de79a3452286fb60fee80a53430317cba0

commit_message:
Add elasticsearch exporter

This adds a chart for an elasticsearch exporter to expose metrics
for prometheus. This also moves the exporter to be included as
part of the chart it's meant to target as opposed to its own
separate chart

Change-Id: I491f4d1efba633827d8a6255218daeb9d427f922

commit_message:
Update doc theme to use current logo

We switched to a new logo some time ago, but since the releases
repo uses a customized doc theme it still had the old logo in
the generated HTML output.

This patch keeps the custom theme, but just switches out the old
logo for the new one.

Change-Id: I368ec2e31055d279b5701cfbbec8a78111e73cb2

commit_message:
Enable congress-tempest-plugin to use in congress

This commit enables to use congress-tempest-plugin instead of intree
repo and also enables heat, murano, aodh tempest plugins to fix the
corresponding congress tempest tests to run.

And also, fixes the gate failure in aodh tests, due to recent change in
aodh to remove the threshold_rule I7ccf930f2ad0316dbda0675a2ec0344e61986022,
so this commit removes the same from congress repo.

dsvm HA tests are disabled.

Depends-On: I5c26c8e77f15f9ea0f075dc23e7249bba5a56e8c
Partially-Implements blueprint split-tempest-plugin
Closes-Bug:#1742656
Partial-Bug:#1743729

Change-Id: If1774d1993a4f20c99d3c41464bb8a365c3c2132

commit_message:
Zuul: Remove project name

Zuul no longer requires the project-name for in-repo configuration.
Omitting it makes forking or renaming projects easier.

Change-Id: I4504f4c523747be8d834bb8e318427abd02b6ab3

commit_message:
Update prometheus metrics gathering in post-job

This updates the prometheus metrics gathering role to dynamically
detect deployed namespaces instead of using hardcoded tasks for
each namespace. This allows the use of this job in openstack-helm
without needing to manually add additional namespaces

Change-Id: I2304aceab8dcda5471af708f57924193f03ee8f3

[{'created': '2018-01-08 23:10:19.000000000', 'message': "Update openstacksdk construction for forward compat

The next release of python-openstacksdk is going to break the code
that's in heat right now. This adds support for both old and new apis.

It also adds a functional test job to run heat with master branch of
openstacksdk so we can make sure both work. We can get rid of that job
once the new version is released.

Change-Id: Idf0acebf7b3774db26e335b3f3229227bfe68502
Depends-On: I52fde4df188fc2747776c4b65bc7ae68c6e82f06

that's in heat right now. This adds support for both old and new apis.

It also adds a functional test job to run heat with master branch of
openstacksdk so we can make sure both work. We can get rid of that job
once the new version is released.

Change-Id: Idf0acebf7b3774db26e335b3f3229227bfe68502
Depends-On: I52fde4df188fc2747776c4b65bc7ae68c6e82f06
"}, {'created': '2018-02-02 18:00:54.000000000', 'message': "Update openstacksdk construction for forward compat

The queens release of python-openstacksdk breaks the sdk and senlin code
that's in heat right now. This adds support for both old and new apis.

python-senlinclient is actually just a thin wrapper around
python-openstacksdk. Instead of reworking the constructor in the Senlin
plugin to be upwards-compatible with the upcoming python-openstacksdk
release, just remove use of python-senlinclient and use the openstacksdk
client plugin instead.

Change-Id: Idf0acebf7b3774db26e335b3f3229227bfe68502

commit_message:
Update openstacksdk construction

The queens release of python-openstacksdk breaks the sdk and senlin code
that's in heat right now. This shifts us to the new world order.

python-senlinclient is actually just a thin wrapper around
python-openstacksdk. Instead of reworking the constructor in the Senlin
plugin, just remove use of python-senlinclient and use the openstacksdk
client plugin instead.

Change-Id: Idf0acebf7b3774db26e335b3f3229227bfe68502

commit_message:
Collect logs to a subfolder properly

The backport of https://review.openstack.org/522794
was incomplete, resulting in the logs still being
put in the same folder as the zuul logs, mixing
everything up and overwriting the ARA report.

This patch completes the backport properly.

Change-Id: Id75d24812019d7f35f2f674cdf8b00222ddbd6ce

commit_message:
Add a status line for SELinux status

Some gate jobs appear to have SELinux in enforcing mode occasionally.
SELinux support is improving but OSA is not ready to run in enforcing
more until some remaining bugs are fixed.

This patch adds a line that prints the current SELinux status during
testing.

Change-Id: I054c1849e5426801f6fdde761b7f64a2e8867af4

commit_message:
Fedora 25-27 support

Update bifrost to handle fedora as minor changes between
releases have been slightly breaking, and have gone largely
un-noticed since the bulk of bifrost users seem to use
centos or ubuntu.

Added a fedora 26 job to help enforce support moving forward.

Change-Id: I9a654b91edfa52321adccfa5df0c260eb0c9e487
Closes-Bug: #1695969
Closes-Bug: #1695968

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-02-06 22:23:18.000000000', 'message': "Fix Host-assisted Share Migration with IPv4+IPv6

Previously, the Data Service allowed only 1 IP to be specified
for the 'data_node_access_ip' config option, which prevented
Host-assisted Share Migration to be successful on a combination
of backends that include IPv6 and IPv4 export locations.

To fix this, we are adding a new config option and deprecating
the old one. The new one is named 'data_node_access_ips' and
accepts a list of IPs. All IPs included in this list should
correspond to interfaces on the node running the Data Service
and will be allowed access during Host-assisted Share Migration.

Additionally, we are improving the responsiveness of the
Host-assisted Share Migration by using exponential waiters
instead of polynomial. Those waiters are used when managing
resources created by Share Migration.

Closes-bug: #1745436
Partial-bug: #1708491

Change-Id: I1c0b7621ae8192f75f691987b185a4fc6a7228ce
"}]
commit_message:
Fix Host-assisted Share Migration with IPv4+IPv6

Previously, the Data Service allowed only 1 IP to be specified
for the 'data_node_access_ip' config option, which prevented
Host-assisted Share Migration to be successful on a combination
of backends that include IPv6 and IPv4 export locations.

To fix this, we are adding a new config option and deprecating
the old one. The new one is named 'data_node_access_ips' and
accepts a list of IPs. All IPs included in this list should
correspond to interfaces on the node running the Data Service
and will be allowed access during Host-assisted Share Migration.

Additionally, we are improving the responsiveness of the
Host-assisted Share Migration by using exponential waiters
instead of polynomial. Those waiters are used when managing
resources created by Share Migration.

Closes-bug: #1745436
Partial-bug: #1708491

Change-Id: I1c0b7621ae8192f75f691987b185a4fc6a7228ce

Zuul: Remove project name

Zuul no longer requires the project-name for in-repo configuration.
Omitting it makes forking or renaming projects easier.

commit_message:
Add missing pacemaker cindier CA cert mounts

This adds the same CA cert mounts which other pacemaker managed
containers like rabbitmq, redis, and haproxy.

With this change, cinder-backup should work correctly when running SSL
enabled.

Change-Id: I199c03ba36a24e6b1caf535ed285047952ac9eb0
Closes-Bug: #1747326

commit_message:
Zuul: Remove project name

Zuul no longer requires the project-name for in-repo configuration.
Omitting it makes forking or renaming projects easier.

Change-Id: I4f49709c7b152ece6018d5c34f1e3f3124b0ad6f

Even though it was working opening the file in 'read' mode, it really
should be opened in 'write' mode, since we are redirecting the output

commit_message:
When ouputting to /dev/null should open in write mode

Even though it was working opening the file in 'read' mode, it really
should be opened in 'write' mode, since we are redirecting the output
to the file.

Interestingly it does fail in 'read' mode if the command is:
    echo something

But passes in 'write' mode.

Change-Id: Ic67091881e0be377e527b78d270ab48962881ae0

commit_message:
federation api: federation table and db layer

this commit introduces a new `Federation` table to
Magnum database, as well as the necessary DB layer
APIs to access and manage it.

this belongs to the first phase of the implementation
of the federation api. check [1] for more details.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/489609/

Change-Id: Ie8a68cd3198c8fc7930069fd2e55f1cad55b6c9b
Partially-Implements: blueprint federation-api

commit_message:
Remove some no-use code about failover

At line 3994, cinder/volume/manage.py, the replicable volume has
been filtered by its type. It is no need to check again in
function: _failover_volume(), rbd.py.

Change-Id: I9b7fff5813d442fef01717ce842021c92ab30d8a

commit_message:
Replace port 35357 with 5000 for ubuntu guide

Now that the v2.0 API has been removed, we don't have a reason to
include deployment instructions for two separate applications on
different ports. This change updates the guide to be consistent with
recent changes to the ubuntu packages:

  https://git.launchpad.net/~ubuntu-server-dev/ubuntu/+source/keystone/commit/?id=915d787af42096b0fad715e49759cd357e47787e

Change-Id: I4f7f70fa561c77a80b1c88e42a685844ab981afc

commit_message:
Allow setting gmcast.peer_timeout value

In some resource constrained environments particularly during deploy
time percona-cluster nodes can experience time outs during inter-node
communication.

This changes makes the gmcast.peer_timeout configurable based on the
galara cluster documentation:
http://galeracluster.com/documentation-webpages/galeraparameters.html

Warning: Changing this value from the default may have unintended
consequences. This should only be used when constraint's call for it.

Closes-Bug: #1742683

commit_message:
Only run map_instances for Ocata

map_instances only needs to be run during the transition from
Newton to Ocata to map existing instances into a cell. All
new Ocata instances will be automatically mapped to a call.
This change limits the slow running map_instances command to
just run for upgrades to Ocata

Change-Id: Ic2e2df530504284d28cfcab26a71d211342203fa
Closes-Bug: #1743357
(cherry picked from commit a0778a5304871a8c22e48d2d1fd0f59209ae792c)

commit_message:
Batch up map_instances call

nova-manage map_instances maps all instances into a cell in batches
of 50 if max-count is not set. Setting max-count causes the script
to run a single batch of size max-count. The return code of the
script shows if there are still more to do. This change runs
map_instances repeatedly with a batch size of 50000 while rc is 1
and then exists cleanly when a rc 0 is recieved.

Change-Id: Id1184778a5ae94bb3b57348b10d12077b093d6dd
Partial-Bug: #1742115
(cherry picked from commit 69c2626d73c9b5aea6c3e31f6118dc3db715c551)

commit_message:
bagpipe-bgp: OVS support for EVPN

This introduces a driver for E-VPNs for OVS.  This driver
is specifically tailored for use with Neutron OVS agent, it
populates the Ethernet forwarding tables in br-tun that are
setup by Neutron OVS agent.

Related-bug: 1719337
Change-Id: I5205ed764d9a57877a66e014536c7539949973a7

commit_message:
Make osc-functional-devstack-tips actually use tips

The base job has tox_install_siblings: false - which we want. But
that means we need tox_install_siblings: true on the tips job.

While we're at it - add fetch-tox-output so that we have tox log files
in the fetched build output for easier verification of what wound up
installed.

Don't look for ResourceNotFound string in test

The string ResourceNotFound is not in the error string anymore. Look for
the text that is.

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/541033
Change-Id: Id6de1485bcafb41f238f3e74277094ce64a6acf4

commit_message:
Revert grenade jobs to classic drivers

This reverts the grenade job driver changes from commit
fa850c80cbc701f1252dabcd3f514bca0148f54d. Local config settings in the
grenade jobs are used for the previous version (old) devstack plugin in
the grenade run. So the local config defined here must match how we want
the old devstack setup, not the current (new) devstack.

Change-Id: I3d5aa1da6879a0c624b5196632886da32e12d7d7

commit_message:
Update manual testing script and output

Added a wait before checking that action execution takes effect.
The change to asynchronous execution makes the wait sometimes
necessary.

Sample outputs also updated to account for the changes of new
congress version. Notable changes include:
ceilometer removal, nova table additions, neutron table additions,
and neutron-qos extension driver.

Change-Id: I335beb3a5530336aaadac9eae41a0c6c6d099fe5
Release-team: this is a testing-only change

commit_message:
Use openstacksdk for most transitive depends

This should get openstacksdk on to people's machines in advance of
porting ansible modules to use sdk directly. It also lets us just use
sdk for all of the transitive depends.

Leave os-client-config as openstacksdk doesn't depend on it and
transitioning to openstack.config is a better task for the rocky cycle.

Change-Id: I6d26785b3aa1fc75fb0ad2d45684d93e9628f61b

commit_message:
kubectl plugin kuryrvif

This plugin prints out nice information about the pods in the current
namespace. It also supports setting a selector and formatting for the
output.

Implements: blueprint kubectl-plugin
Change-Id: Id2afa262aa602765e1abf7fdd6ecda593b642ce0
Signed-off-by: Antoni Segura Puimedon <antonisp@celebdor.com>

commit_message:
Update iRMC document for classic driver deprecation

As a part of deprecating classic drivers, this patch updates the
documentation of iRMC driver. We still mention the classic drivers with
warning. The description for the classic drivers will be removed in
Rocky.

Change-Id: I6331072b44bf33c6bfa75703bf2ab46dac96a5e7
Related-Bug: #1690185

commit_message:
Handle case when a glance image contains no data

In my experience, it happens when Swift storage backing Glance was
purged, but it can probably also happen if an image never had data
at all. This patch raises a correct exception instead of TypeError.

Switch relevant unit tests to Glance V2, as V1 is long deprecated.

Change-Id: I75e5ae7f46ce3a1506ed6108ff05df3083fd5084
Closes-Bug: #1741223

commit_message:
Use zuul.override_checkout  instead of custom branch_override var

To override the branch correctly in both zuulv3's playbook loading we
have to use override_checkout in the job. This variable already gives us
the information we need to set the override branch, so use that instead
of the custom branch_override variable so we don't have to define it
twice in the job.

Change-Id: Iec7be918f75e3400197748385b287fb945d761ac
(cherry picked from commit dcc5546b49ad7a791a00284999e6db4a802792b1)

commit_message:
Use zuul.override_checkout  instead of custom branch_override var

To override the branch correctly in both zuulv3's playbook loading we
have to use override_checkout in the job. This variable already gives us
the information we need to set the override branch, so use that instead
of the custom branch_override variable so we don't have to define it
twice in the job.

Change-Id: Iec7be918f75e3400197748385b287fb945d761ac
(cherry picked from commit dcc5546b49ad7a791a00284999e6db4a802792b1)

commit_message:
zuul.d: gerritbot: Remove check and gate jobs as now in repo

The gerritbot repository now has a .zuul.yaml file[1] which has the
check and gate jobs defined for it. It is no longer needed to have it
here and also stops us from running the pep8 job twice for submitted
patches.

[1] Commit 4658934d2239c32103c0e04cb32e2af4d44c16f4 in
    openstack/gerritbot

Change-Id: I7e0b64bb4a880c5b100a87164b66841c8a403be9

commit_message:
Remove unused optparse code in trove.db

add_options in trove.db is not used for a long time, and this is the
same situation fofr optparse in python 2.7, so we can safely remove
this part from trove.db.

Closes-Bug: #1553030
Change-Id: I17228eed5c122bce49ce80ec665fe73d6caa1e04
Signed-off-by: Zhao Chao <zhaochao1984@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Remove trailing slash in NODEPOOL_PUPPETLABS_MIRROR

Currently, variable NODEPOOL_PUPPETLABS_MIRROR for centos has an
extra slash character at the end. It seems this is not a problem when
using a mirror, but it fails when using puppetlabs yum repo as the
url [1] gives an 404 error, while [2] works fine.

[1] https://yum.puppetlabs.com//el/7/PC1/x86_64/repodata/repomd.xml
[1] https://yum.puppetlabs.com/el/7/PC1/x86_64/repodata/repomd.xml

Change-Id: Idf3a080322f117e62dec291f3047e9b5408813b9

commit_message:
Update MariaDB CentOS yum mirror URL

The yum mirrors for MariaDB have changes to the directory structure.
This patch updates the directory structure and chooses a faster
mirror from the US to use for installation.

Closes-Bug: 1747740
Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/541699
Change-Id: I5f1ecb71c6125c29d6487bef6c2be215c1b561c1

commit_message:
Remove impossible tests

We haven't managed to pass functional tests for CentOS this cycle,
it seems overly ambitious to think the upgrade tests would pass.

We also removed the periodics from centos/suse, because they are
all timing out, and therefore are using resources for nothing.
We keep the check jobs to be aware of timings.

Change-Id: I4900cbc22da83582ddd48af7df99d66de1a129f9

commit_message:
Do not pass credentials to the ramdisk on cleaning

Currently the driver_info is passed as is to the ramdisk when calling
get_clean_steps or execute_clean_step. This may lead to their exposure,
as ironic<->ramdisk communication is currently not secure.

This change applies the same logic we use in the API to filter
the fields.

Change-Id: I4fd44786fea6c7092d2b0029cea6d680d31babde
Closes-Bug: #1744836
(cherry picked from commit c2185469c4a9246fa62ceae76676a08ed84e686d)

Zuul: Remove project name

Zuul no longer requires the project-name for in-repo configuration.
Omitting it makes forking or renaming projects easier.

commit_message:
Storwize: avoid ascii code error for ssh response stderr

If there are non-ascii characters in the ssh response stderr, The
below type of message handling exception will blow up:
UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec can't decode byte <hex val>
in position xx:ordinal not in range(128).

This patch uses safe_decode for the stderr to avoid the ascii code
error.

Change-Id: Id630391dde7149095fc258c0f0da7d9829d1388a
Closes-Bug:  1745098

commit_message:
relnote: clearly mention django-openstack-auth needs uninstall

Before upgrading horizon, django-openstack-auth needs to be
uninstalled. Otherwise, openstack_auth python module will be
maintained by both django-openstack-auth and horizon python package
and this potentially brings confusion.

blueprint merge-openstack-auth

Change-Id: Iedf9b6087e35caf4f196780e94247554b360dd0e

commit_message:
Fix ansible pipelining

There's a bug in Ansible 2.4 where the normal option to enable
pipelining is being ignored. To workaround this issue we need to set
"ANSIBLE_PIPELINING" and "ANSIBLE_SSH_PIPELINING".

See https://github.com/ansible/ansible/issues/31125 for more details.

Change-Id: Ib7edc688a2fbc4a3755bec3fbb78a1778219ff14
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Disable plan upload/edit button during transition

The "Upload Files and Create/Edit Plan" button is currently not being
disabled after it has been clicked and while the create/update process
is still running. Clicking it twice results in an error and should not
be possible in the first place.

This patch disables the button during a transition by checking the
`isTransitioningPlan` prop in addition to the `canSubmit` prop.

Change-Id: I4324ca828ff2ea1eccafa8d7faae7a181b736b2c
Closes-Bug: #1747932

commit_message:
Remove leftover UCA variables

Previously the repo_build role implemented its own tasks for
setting up the UCA repository. It was later shifted to the
pip_install role and for Queens it's in the openstack_hosts
role.

In Queens these variables are no longer used. In Pike and
before these variables interfere with the values set out in
the pip_install role which are the canonical values.

As such, we remove them from the role and this patch will
need to be ported back.

Backport note:
Adjusted changes to suit the newton branch which supports
two versions of Ubuntu and had slightly different values.

Change-Id: If499287a5d346bb7c5d0775c21f55a1f73d6db89
(cherry picked from commit 1948d899a5c76143cf24c1a8ae162906a8e1faf1)

commit_message:
Allow not resolving outputs on get stacks

Depending on the stack complexity, resolving outputs of a Heat stack can
be fairly expensive. The API has a parameter to disable output
resolution: this adds this parameter to the get_stack call, and use it
in places where outputs are superfluous.

Change-Id: I779e451c9f058a954a0526404489a4fb1b39ee9c

commit_message:
Update curl request documentation to remove v2.0

The curl examples we keep in our documentation contain examples for
interacting with the now removed v2.0 APIs. This commit removes those
examples since we no long support v2.0, except for the ec2token API
until the T release. The curl examples didn't have any v2.0 ec2token
examples.

Change-Id: I7e16421873de1c2ebf13db971bef80a2d74e5823

commit_message:
Test case: new standard resource class unusable

If the placement service code is newer than that of the compute service,
new standard resource classes may have been introduced in placement
which compute doesn't yet know about.  These resource classes will be
unusable due to the noted bug.

This change set adds a test case demonstrating the bug.

Change-Id: I71ce6796beb23c4bb3d637dab5ca0e620274b2fc
Partial-Bug: #1746615

commit_message:
Change directories to os-service-types during update

The update script framework calls the update function with an argument
of the directory of the project we're trying to update. The update
script needs to pushd into it before curling the new content.

Change-Id: Ic569aee5716ca32e755adda02f149359b532c4fc

commit_message:
Remove leftover UCA variables

Previously the repo_build role implemented its own tasks for
setting up the UCA repository. It was later shifted to the
pip_install role and for Queens it's in the openstack_hosts
role.

In Queens these variables are no longer used. In Pike and
before these variables interfere with the values set out in
the pip_install role which are the canonical values.

As such, we remove them from the role and this patch will
need to be ported back.

Change-Id: If499287a5d346bb7c5d0775c21f55a1f73d6db89
(cherry picked from commit 1948d899a5c76143cf24c1a8ae162906a8e1faf1)

commit_message:
Remove leftover UCA variables

Previously the repo_build role implemented its own tasks for
setting up the UCA repository. It was later shifted to the
pip_install role and for Queens it's in the openstack_hosts
role.

In Queens these variables are no longer used. In Pike and
before these variables interfere with the values set out in
the pip_install role which are the canonical values.

As such, we remove them from the role and this patch will
need to be ported back.

Change-Id: If499287a5d346bb7c5d0775c21f55a1f73d6db89
(cherry picked from commit 1948d899a5c76143cf24c1a8ae162906a8e1faf1)

commit_message:
Remove use of construct lib FieldError exception

Version 2.8.22 of the construct lib has introduced a change that
removed the core.FieldError exception. The check now uses the
parent exception - core.ConstructError.

Change-Id: I31922c2afc2018a4f6f7ba48094388070537a13f
Closes-Bug: 1745208
(cherry picked from commit a6f2805bbc2d51918a027ca519ada793cb6c9cf9)

commit_message:
Make heat parameter plugin_dirs configurable

Heat has an additional configuration for plugin_dirs
parameter. This parameter provides a list of directories
to search for plug-ins. This change allows configuration
of plugin_dirs parameter in heat.conf file. This change
will allow a user to set this value, if required. Else
$::os_service_default will be used and the parameter will
not be added to the config file, as it is done today.

Change-Id: I636d52f867ee447eaf0e1e80bf9fdc30c91f4ec1
(cherry picked from commit 56cbd7c89bfc99f6a962319f478d75dbf35e8335)

commit_message:
Drop MongoDB installation and API file configurations

Ceilometer no longer stores any data so the MongoDB installation
playbook is not used.  In addition, it no longer has an API so
the api-paste file is useless as well.

Closes-Bug: #1747612

commit_message:
Make heat parameter plugin_dirs configurable

Heat has an additional configuration for plugin_dirs
parameter. This parameter provides a list of directories
to search for plug-ins. This change allows configuration
of plugin_dirs parameter in heat.conf file. This change
will allow a user to set this value, if required. Else
$::os_service_default will be used and the parameter will
not be added to the config file, as it is done today.

Change-Id: I636d52f867ee447eaf0e1e80bf9fdc30c91f4ec1
(cherry picked from commit 56cbd7c89bfc99f6a962319f478d75dbf35e8335)

commit_message:
Use zuul.override_checkout  instead of custom branch_override var

To override the branch correctly in both zuulv3's playbook loading we
have to use override_checkout in the job. This variable already gives us
the information we need to set the override branch, so use that instead
of the custom branch_override variable so we don't have to define it
twice in the job.

Change-Id: Iec7be918f75e3400197748385b287fb945d761ac

commit_message:
Fix handling of 'timeout' parameter to power methods

The PowerInterface methods set_power_state() and reboot() were enhanced
to take a 'timeout' parameter [1]. To handle Interfaces that didn't
support timeout, conductor.utils.node_power_action() used
reflection.get_signature() to determine whether or not the node's
PowerInterface's methods could handle a timeout parameter.

It turns out that there was a bug with the
ironic_lib.metrics.timer decorator [2], such that
reflection.get_signature() did not return the method parameters. This
means that for PowerInterfaces that had this decorator, the conductor
would incorrectly think that 'timeout' was not supported, even if it
were supported.

Instead of trying to decide whether a PowerInterface supports 'timeout',
the conductor now assumes that it does. This patch changes all in-tree
PowerInterfaces so that they accept a 'timeout' parameter for reboot()
and set_power_state().

For any out-of-tree implementations that don't accept a 'timeout'
parameter, a TypeError exception will be raised.

[1] f15d5b9a37260b3876f9dadeb030412e6e1053b2
[2] https://bugs.launchpad.net/ironic/+bug/1746730

Closes-Bug: #1746849
Change-Id: Iae28e94c34d4d69593644d0e5f4542558db9bb79

commit_message:
Remove hard-coded host group value

This patch removes the hardcoded haproxy_all value and replaces
it with ansible_play_hosts instead.

Change-Id: I8a8a71f49d01748c4674ea8402c8279edbd71559

commit_message:
Make the agent distributed using hashring and notifications

Use oslo messaging notifier + listener to group nodes in a tooz
hashring.

Each node running the agent will join the ring and maintain its
membership by sending periodic notifications. Each node uses the
hashring to report state for its subset of ironic nodes. When
nodes no longer recives notifications from a member it is removed
from the hashring.

Related-Bug: #1658964
Change-Id: I783fd889259be78aea1914630aad9dc7829b5e8e

commit_message:
Update MariaDB CentOS yum mirror URL

The yum mirrors for MariaDB have changes to the directory structure.

commit_message:
Include outputs in rolling update of ResourceGroup

The template generated by ResourceGroup should include outputs that
reference any needed resource attributes. However, previously it only did
so when rolling updates were not enabled by an update_policy.

Change-Id: Ice7a92fe8d2b14e2470d9089a8e191c8385994f1
Closes-Bug: #1741981
Partial-Bug: #1731349
Related-Bug: #1660831

commit_message:
queens release doc fix part 1

More patches might follow

Update 0(pacth 1):
1.remove unnecessary files
2.reorg doc directory

Update 1(patch 2):
add releasenotes and cleanup the internal-api spec

Update 2(patch 3):
1.added a new releasenote for generic-driver
2.fixed errors in the other four earlier releasenotes
3.add comment in cyborg/object/accelerator.py and deployable.py to
let user better know the meanings of the table entries.

Signed-off-by: zhipengh <huangzhipeng@huawei.com>

commit_message:
Fix nsenter commands on centos

The follow-context switch is not valid on early releases of systemd. This
change removes the optional switch so that nsenter can work on all of
our platforms.

Change-Id: I13d05ba8bcfe785257a9cf98dbdb6024ec937816
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

Currently the driver_info is passed as is to the ramdisk when calling

commit_message:
Do not pass credentials to the ramdisk on cleaning

Currently the driver_info is passed as is to the ramdisk when calling
get_clean_steps or execute_clean_step. This may lead to their exposure,
as ironic<->ramdisk communication is currently not secure.

This change applies the same logic we use in the API to filter
the fields.

Change-Id: I4fd44786fea6c7092d2b0029cea6d680d31babde
Closes-Bug: #1744836

commit_message:
Remove leftover UCA variables

Previously the repo_build role implemented its own tasks for
setting up the UCA repository. It was later shifted to the
pip_install role and for Queens it's in the openstack_hosts
role.

In Queens these variables are no longer used. In Pike and
before these variables interfere with the values set out in
the pip_install role which are the canonical values.

As such, we remove them from the role and this patch will
need to be ported back.

Change-Id: If499287a5d346bb7c5d0775c21f55a1f73d6db89

commit_message:
Zuul: Remove project name

Zuul no longer requires the project-name for in-repo configuration.
Omitting it makes forking or renaming projects easier.

Change-Id: I53c6bf99a218adb6a14f6fe339caa82a5439541d

subject: Added cache options to the config file
messages:
[{'account_id': 27008, 'date': '2017-12-16 17:38:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 27008, 'date': '2017-12-18 19:16:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8731, 'date': '2017-12-19 10:54:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

Can you please explain the main reason why you decided to make this patch? Did you hit some problem with the hardcoded values we use?

Honestly, I'm not sure about the idea of this patch. On one hand, I understand that we might want to make these caches configurable. On another hand, all these things are not so relevant to uses. Especially, caching of workflow specifications because specification itself is a purely an implementation thing, users probably won't have any idea about what it is. Caching task executions makes more sense but we need to have a clear description of it, and I'm not sure we need two config options for that."}, {'account_id': 27008, 'date': '2017-12-20 08:05:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

First of all, sorry for my English :)
I have a simple goal. I want that Mistral's cluster can process minimum 2500 tasks per minute. I tested the ocata version and found some concerns. And it is one of them. Performance has improved after I increased the cache size of workflow specification.
I will retest last 5.2.0 release and I will come with results and fixes after the New Year if necessary.
I leave the status ticket in WIP."}, {'account_id': 27008, 'date': '2018-02-07 15:21:40.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-01-06 16:56:35.000000000', 'message': 'refactor keystone-ldap

* replace singletons with provide_charm_instance (in the code and tests)
* select an openstack release based on keystone package due to the lack
of openstack-origin from the principal layer (this is a subordinate, see
https://git.io/vNTyx)
* use reactive triggers to drop config.complete (new configuration
completeness) and config.rendered (non-stale config is rendered) on
config.changed
* do not check config completeness on every event - only when config has
actually changed
* remove the domain configuration file when relation with keystone is
removed (service restart should be performed on the keystone charm side)
* modify unit tests to reflect the changes

Change-Id: Ied4b6ed64354e3de3c78e6ac809666ee9ae29d1a
Closes-Bug: #1741661

commit_message:
refactor keystone-ldap

* replace singletons with provide_charm_instance (in the code and tests)
* select an openstack release based on keystone package due to the lack
of openstack-origin from the principal layer (this is a subordinate, see
https://git.io/vNTyx)
* use reactive triggers to drop config.complete (new configuration
completeness) and config.rendered (non-stale config is rendered) on
config.changed
* do not check config completeness on every event - only when config has
actually changed
* remove the domain configuration file when relation with keystone is
removed (service restart should be performed on the keystone charm side)
* replace path_hash with file_hash (path_hash returns a new dict)
* modify unit tests to reflect the changes

Change-Id: Ied4b6ed64354e3de3c78e6ac809666ee9ae29d1a
Closes-Bug: #1741661

commit_message:
Make the cron trigger execution interval configurable

The cron_trigger subsystem in Mistral queries the database every second
to look for triggers that require execution. This can be very wasteful
if your deployment only has cron triggers that run infrequently (every
hour or day etc.). Letting operators configure this value reduces the
load and allows the cron triggers to be useful in more scenarios.

Operators do need to be aware that this configuration would limit the
frequency of execution. For example, if the value is set to 600 then cron
triggers configured to run every minute will only run every 10 minutes.

Related-Bug: #1747386
Change-Id: I9060253bc416be28af4ef81f3edf694059d92066

commit_message:
Storwize: modify the self._helpers to backend_helper

The helper used for volume attaching should be backend_helper rather
than self._helpers.
This patch modifies the self._helpers to backend_helper.

Change-Id: Ia18ca2f7862d53fc6ea49ff874eae7b63fae8cb8
Close-Bug: 1746876

commit_message:
Add send_cluster_metrics configuration parameter

Added configuration parameter, send_cluster_metrics, to magnum.conf
with default value of True. If set to True, periodic tasks will pull
COE data and send to ceilometer. This parameter can be set to False to
disable periodic collection of data to avoid unnecessary load from the
cluster.

Closes-Bug: #1668330
Related-Bug: #1746510

Change-Id: I9945293e7b2b52731f6e220d0925c1f6ad097caa

commit_message:
Add label availability_zone

Add a new label 'availability_zone' allowing users to specify the AZ
the nodes should be deployed in. Only one AZ can be passed for this
first implementation.

Change-Id: I9e55d7631191fffa6cc6b9bebbeb4faf2497815b
Partially-Implements: blueprint magnum-availability-zones

commit_message:
Log when we bail out without checking a resource

There's nothing more frustrating than trying to debug when a message
appears to get lost without rhyme or reason. When we're not going to
process a resource (because it has already been replaced), log what is
happening so that we can see it when debugging.

Change-Id: I89d4b51205798d3c930f0132c81ff987d46382c7

[{'created': '2018-01-09 16:23:01.000000000', 'message': 'Stable keepalived priorities

The calculation of the keepalived priority depended on the set of hosts
in the ansible_play_hosts variable. This meant that priorites changed
when the playbook was limited to only run on a subset of the hosts in
the "haproxy" group (eg. when reinstalling just one node).

This change replaces ansible_play_hosts by groups["haproxy"] so that the
priority calculation is stable as long as the set of haproxy nodes does
not change. It also simplifies the priority calculation without
changeing the result.

This change does not change the configuration in case the playbook is

if it is run with --limit.

commit_message:
Stable keepalived priorities

The calculation of the keepalived priority depended on the set of hosts
in the ansible_play_hosts variable. This meant that priorites changed
when the playbook was limited to only run on a subset of the hosts in
the "haproxy" group (eg. when reinstalling just one node).

This change replaces ansible_play_hosts by groups["haproxy"] so that the
priority calculation is stable as long as the set of haproxy nodes does
not change. It also simplifies the priority calculation without
changeing the result.

This change does not change the configuration in case the playbook is
run without --limit and ensures that the configuration does not change
if it is run with --limit.

Change-Id: I378351954fbed7b1fc31303c60e4575ddad9cf1d
(cherry picked from commit 78ed74957dfbd1bb151d0e6b5187fa0c263881ad)

commit_message:
BGPVPN OVO: use new-style DB facade to query IPAllocations

This is a workaround for bug 1746996, which relies on using
an explicit SQLAlchemy DB query in place of OVO object lookups.
This allows to control the DB facade used, and avoid the use of
the old-style facade still used by Neutron OVO code, to prefer
to new-style facade that needs to be used to allow accessing
IPAllocations created in the same session via the new-style
facade.

Related-Bug: 1746996
Change-Id: I82d3c1358746085cb801a2876f7a075564d5863c

commit_message:
Exiting with user friendly message and SystemExit()

If you return anything as string to sys.exit method, the system exit
status is one (i.e. failure).
Added user friendly print message and returned without any exit code.

Closes-Bug: #1747690

Change-Id: I107cc1ad4b8d6d0ebee1127fc1e57db55c7cd839

commit_message:
[Devstack] Replace tap with veth

This patch replace tap interfaces by veth pairs which
ensures that port is always present in ovs even when VM
is powered off.

Closes-Bug: #1722158

Change-Id: I04ff6a97bebf15636a794b51f748c62eda627d36
(cherry picked from commit f357c76cd508ac53844141602c4ba0127b63a7de)

commit_message:
image_upload: allow ctrl-c

Allow operators to run ctrl-c during image uplaod and gracefully exit.

Change-Id: I6dafde0cc9326a6f0f4b9cee35354cc7142582d1
Closes-Bug: #1746724

commit_message:
Warn user about guessing content type deprecation.

In ironic extension types is not fully supported. This lead to
404 NOT FOUND errors when trying to point to resource names
with dots if pecan config option ``guess_content_type_from_ext``
is set to True (default value).

Warn user that this option will be disabled in next release.

Change-Id: Ic3eda63d26537dfa5c03618e166449307fbcdda0
Closes-Bug: #1643995
Co-Authored-By: Andrew Balfour <andrew.balfour@oracle.com>

commit_message:
Clean up dependencies (keystone, tripleo-common)

Dependency was renamed on pypi from msgpack-python to msgpack,
and keystone switched to the new name for Queens.

Also, tripleo-common migrated from gitdb to GitPython, adjust
dependencies accordingly as they started to cause conflicts.

Change-Id: I97ddf5333f22bfd7ebcbfdfa130b328d7c077cf9

commit_message:
placement doc: Conflict caveat for DELETE APIs

Since the DELETE /resource_providers/{u}/inventories and .../traits APIs
don't have a way to accept generation, they're not "threadsafe" in the
sense of multiple client threads managing traits/inventories for the
same provider.  This change adds a note to the documentation for these
APIs to this effect, suggesting the use of PUT with empty
traits/inventories instead.

Change-Id: Icfd79cc1f5a912131845a22b4fe900147b19f934
Closes-Bug: #1746373

[{'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2018-02-05 09:49:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2018-02-05 09:51:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ben, I guess we'll need to push a new release for tripleo-repos after this gets merged?"}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2018-02-05 16:26:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

> Ben, I guess we'll need to push a new release for tripleo-repos
 > after this gets merged?

We don't actually use released tripleo-repos.  Right now the docs just point to the current dlrn repo, so people will get the new version as soon as it merges and gets built.

Ideally I would like to have some sort of a sync job that puts a tripleo-repos package in some easily found location like tripleo.org/tripleo-repos.rpm, but that hasn't actually happened yet."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2018-02-07 13:23:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2'}]

commit_message:
Implement update VNFFG functionality

Until now there was no implementation of updating an existing
VNFFG with the use of the 'vnffgd-template' parameter which is
introduced in the Tacker client side. This patch addresses exactly
that.

Implements: blueprint update-vnffg

Change-Id: I8fa748a76fd479649be5dd7a19244f7143849687
Signed-off-by: Dimitrios Markou <mardim@intracom-telecom.com>
